        <RecipeInfo id="1">

            <RecipeTitle>Apple Cranberry Stuffed Pork Roast</RecipeTitle>

            <RecipePictureList>
                <RecipePicture>cranberry_pork</RecipePicture>
                <RecipePicture>cranberry_pork</RecipePicture>
                <RecipePicture>cranberry_pork</RecipePicture>
            </RecipePictureList>

            <RecipeSummary>
                <RecipeSummaryOrigin>Europe</RecipeSummaryOrigin>
                <RecipeSummaryPreparationTime>20 mins</RecipeSummaryPreparationTime>
                <RecipeSummaryCookingTime>60 mins</RecipeSummaryCookingTime>
                <RecipeSummaryPortions>6-8</RecipeSummaryPortions>
                <RecipeSummaryCalories>1200</RecipeSummaryCalories>
                <RecipeSummaryDescription>Some medical facilities require that nurses acknowledge their acceptance and resumption of care from the previous nursing shift. This can include a statement that describes the patient when the nurse reported to the unit. This note is usually created after a brief bedside report has been made where both nurses were present and discussing the patient's health status and plan of care in the patient's room. Only one note needed per two 12 hour shifts (make sure that both RNs have signed the same note). Some hospitals have the night nurses start the next day's note so that the oncoming day shift can have it ready to be annotated and signed.
                </RecipeSummaryDescription>
            </RecipeSummary>

            <RecipeIngredientsList>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>apple cider</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1 cup</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>cider vinegar</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/2 cup</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>packed light brown sugar</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>3/4 cup</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>shallot, peeled, thinly sliced</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>dried apples (packed)</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1 1/2 cups</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>dried cranberries</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/2 cup</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>grated fresh ginger</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1 Tbsp</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>ground allspice</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/2 teaspoon</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>cayenne pepper</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/8 to 1/4 teaspoon</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>pound boneless center-cut pork loin roast (short and wide - about 7-8 inches long and 4-5 inches wide)
                    </RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>2 1/2</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
                    </RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
            </RecipeIngredientsList>

            <RecipeStepsList>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 1:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Before starting on the pork, put the pork roast in the freezer for 30 minutes to make it easier to cut. While the pork is chilling, you can make the filling.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 2:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Bring all the filling ingredients to simmer in medium saucepan over medium-high heat. Cover, reduce heat to low, and cook until apples are very soft, about 20 minutes. Strain through a fine-mesh sieve, reserving the liquid. Use a rubber spatula to press against the apple mixture in the sieve to extract as much liquid out as possible. Return liquid to saucepan and simmer over medium-high heat until reduced to 1/2 cup, about 5 minutes. Remove from heat, set aside and reserve this liquid for use as a glaze. Pulse apple mixture in food processor, about fifteen 1-second pulses. Set aside.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                    <RecipeStepVideo>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rwjk6zmjP70</RecipeStepVideo>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 3:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Preheat oven to 350Â°F or prepare your grill for indirect heat. You will be "double-butterflying" the pork roast. Lay the roast down, fat side up. Insert the knife into the roast 1/2-inch horizontally from the bottom of the roast, along the long side of the roast. Make a long cut along the bottom of the roast, stopping 1/2 inch before the edge of the roast. You might find it easier to handle by starting at a corner of the roast. Open up the roast and continue to cut through the thicker half of the roast, again keeping 1/2 inch from the bottom. Repeat until the roast is an even 1/2-inch thickness all over when laid out. If necessary, pound the roast to an even thickness with a meat pounder.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                    <RecipeStepImage>apple-cran-stuffed-pork-step-3</RecipeStepImage>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 4:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Season the inside of the roast well with salt and pepper. Spread out the filling on the roast, leaving a 1/2-inch border from the edges. Starting with the short side of the roast, roll it up very tightly. Secure with kitchen twine at 1-inch intervals. Season the outside of the roast generously with salt and pepper.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                    <RecipeStepImage>apple-cran-stuffed-pork-step-4</RecipeStepImage>
                    <RecipeStepVideo>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hz-AWLdvjMg</RecipeStepVideo>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 5:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Place roast on a rack in a roasting pan, place in oven, on the middle rack. You can also grill the roast, using indirect heat either gas or charcoal. If you re using charcoal, use about 5 pounds of coals, bank them to one side. Preheat the grill, covered. Wipe the grates with olive oil. Place roast, fat side up, on the side of the grill that has no coals underneath. Place the lid on the grill, with the vent directly over the roast. If you are grilling with gas, place all the burners on high for 15 minutes to heat the grates, brush grates with olive oil, turn off the middle burner, place roast fat-side up on middle burner. If you are grilling, turn roast half way through the cooking. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes, until the internal temperature of the roast is 130 to 135 degrees. Brush with half of the glaze and cook for 5 minutes longer. Remove the roast from the oven or grill. Place it on a cutting board. Tent it with foil to rest and keep warm for 15 minutes before slicing.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 6:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Slice into 1/2-inch wide pieces, removing the cooking twine as you cut the roast. Serve with remaining glaze.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
            </RecipeStepsList>

        </RecipeInfo>
        <RecipeInfo id="2">
            
            <RecipeTitle>Angel Hair Pasta with Clams, Cherry Tomatoes, and Basil</RecipeTitle>
            
            <RecipePictureList>
                <RecipePicture>angel_pasta</RecipePicture>
                <RecipePicture>angel_pasta_2</RecipePicture>
            </RecipePictureList>
            
            <RecipeSummary>
                <RecipeSummaryOrigin>Europe</RecipeSummaryOrigin>
                <RecipeSummaryPreparationTime>15 mins</RecipeSummaryPreparationTime>
                <RecipeSummaryCookingTime>15 mins</RecipeSummaryCookingTime>
                <RecipeSummaryPortions>2-3</RecipeSummaryPortions>
                <RecipeSummaryCalories>1100</RecipeSummaryCalories>
                <RecipeSummaryDescription>Hereâs a quick and easy, kid-pleasing angel hair pasta dish we made recently with chopped canned clams and cherry tomatoes and basil from the garden. I say âkid pleasingâ because all kids will come back for more. Even big kids will behave the same, but I think that older ones would like this too.
                </RecipeSummaryDescription>
            </RecipeSummary>
            
            <RecipeIngredientsList>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>cherry tomatoes, sliced in half'</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>30</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>salt</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/4 teaspoon</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>chopped fresh basil, divided</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>4 Tbsp</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>olive oil</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/4 cup</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>sliced shallots</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>1/2 cups</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>minced garlic</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>2 cloves</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>chopped clams (and their juices)</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>2 6-ounce cans</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>capellini or angel hair pasta</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>8 ounce</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
                <RecipeIngredient>
                    <RecipeIngredientsName>Salt for the pasta water</RecipeIngredientsName>
                    <RecipeIngredientsQuantity>-</RecipeIngredientsQuantity>
                </RecipeIngredient>
            </RecipeIngredientsList>
            
            <RecipeStepsList>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 1:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Place sliced cherry tomatoes in a bowl. Toss with 1/4 teaspoon of salt and 2 Tbsp of the chopped fresh basil. Set aside.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 2:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil (4 quarts of water, 2 Tbsp salt). While the water is coming to a boil, prep the shallots and garlic and start the sauce.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 3:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Heat the olive oil in a large sautÃ© pan on medium heat. Add the sliced shallots and cook until translucent, stirring often. Add the garlic and cook for 30 seconds more. Add the tomatoes and cook for 2 minutes. Add the chopped clams with their juices. Reduce the heat to low and let simmer at a low temperature while the pasta is cooking.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 4:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Once the salted pasta water comes to a rolling boil, add pasta and cook, uncovered at high heat until al dente, no more than 2 minutes. Drain the pasta, reserving 1/4 cup of the pasta water. Add the 1/4 cup of pasta water to the sauce in the sautÃ© pan.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 5:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Add the pasta to the cherry tomato mixture and toss to combine. Stir in the remaining 2 Tbsp chopped fresh basil.
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
                <RecipeStep>
                    <RecipeStepName>Step 6:</RecipeStepName>
                    <RecipeStepDescription>Serve immediately!
                    </RecipeStepDescription>
                </RecipeStep>
            </RecipeStepsList>
            
        </RecipeInfo>
